headline: Campbell’s Braces for Trump Tariffs to Hit Pantry Staples
summary: Pantry staples are in line for a hit from President Trump’s tariffs.  Campbell’s said that it’s taking a variety of steps to minimize the impact of tariffs, including working with suppliers and looking for alternative sources.  Where “absolutely necessary,” Campbell’s Chief Financial Officer Carrie Anderson said the company would consider raising prices.

headline: Campbell's earnings: Shipment timing gave big boost to snack brand
summary: The Campbell's Company (CPB) — the food brand known for its various canned soups and snacks — posted its fiscal third quarter earnings results Monday morning, topping Wall Street estimates on the top and bottom line. BofA Securities Food & Beverage Analyst Peter Galbo — who has an Underperform rating and a $37 per share price target on Campbell's stock — comes on The Morning Brief to talk more about Campbell's product pricing and the state of the US consumer. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Morning Brief here.

headline: Home Cooking Is Back at Pandemic Levels, Campbell’s Says
summary: Cautious consumers are eating out less and instead loading up on condensed soups, broths and Italian sauces, as they make "more deliberate choices" on food spending, says Campbell's. Softening consumer sentiment—first seen in January—has continued, said Chief Executive Mick Beekhuizen in prepared remarks for the company's quarterly earnings.
